---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import EditorialNote from "../../components/EditorialNote.astro";
import RelatedLinks from "../../components/RelatedLinks.astro";
import { appliances } from "../../data/appliances";
import { guides } from "../../data/guides";

const title = "How to Calculate Electricity Cost from Watts and kWh";
const description = "Learn the electricity cost formula: watts / 1000 x hours used x cost per kWh. Use it to estimate appliance running cost per day, month, or year.";
const relatedCalculatorSlugs = [
  "space-heater-cost-calculator",
  "electric-oven-cost-calculator",
  "gaming-pc-electricity-cost-calculator",
  "pool-pump-electricity-cost-calculator",
];
const relatedCalculatorLinks = appliances
  .filter((appliance) => relatedCalculatorSlugs.includes(appliance.slug))
  .map((appliance) => ({
    eyebrow: appliance.category,
    title: `${appliance.name} Cost Calculator`,
    description: `${appliance.wattsTypical}W typical estimate`,
    href: `/calculators/${appliance.slug}/`,
  }));
const relatedGuideLinks = guides
  .filter((guide) => guide.slug !== "how-to-calculate-electricity-cost")
  .slice(0, 3)
  .map((guide) => ({
    eyebrow: guide.category,
    title: guide.title,
    description: guide.description,
    href: `/guides/${guide.slug}/`,
  }));
const articleSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  headline: "How to Calculate Electricity Cost",
  description,
  author: { "@type": "Organization", name: "WattCostGuide" },
  publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: "WattCostGuide" },
  mainEntityOfPage: "https://wattcostguide.com/guides/how-to-calculate-electricity-cost/",
};
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <a href="/">Home</a>
    <span>/</span>
    <a href="/guides/">Guides</a>
  </nav>

  <section class="page-header">
    <p class="eyebrow">Basics</p>
    <h1>How to Calculate Electricity Cost</h1>
    <p>To estimate appliance running cost, convert watts to kilowatts, multiply by hours used, then multiply by your electricity rate.</p>
  </section>

  <EditorialNote note="This guide uses the same cost formula as the appliance calculators. Actual bills may include taxes, fees, delivery charges, and time-of-use pricing." />

  <section class="section article-block">
    <h2>The formula</h2>
    <pre><code>Cost = Watts / 1000 x Hours Used x Electricity Rate</code></pre>
    <p>
      Watts measure power. Kilowatt-hours measure energy over time. Your electric bill usually charges by
      kilowatt-hour, written as kWh.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section article-block">
    <h2>Step-by-step method</h2>
    <p>
      Start by finding the appliance wattage. This may be printed on a label, listed in the manual, or shown
      in product specifications. If the device lists amps and volts instead of watts, multiply amps by volts
      to estimate watts.
    </p>
    <p>
      Next, estimate how many hours the appliance actually runs. For a hair dryer or microwave, this may be
      minutes per use. For a space heater or air conditioner, it may be several hours. For appliances that
      cycle on and off, such as refrigerators or dehumidifiers, estimate active runtime rather than the full
      time plugged in.
    </p>
    <p>
      Finally, use your electricity rate. A simple estimate can use the average cost per kWh from your bill.
      If you have time-of-use pricing, use the rate that applies when the appliance usually runs.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>Example calculation</h2>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Input</th>
            <th>Example value</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Appliance wattage</td>
            <td>1,500 watts</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Usage time</td>
            <td>4 hours</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Electricity rate</td>
            <td>$0.18 per kWh</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Estimated cost</td>
            <td>$1.08</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section article-block">
    <h2>What can change the result?</h2>
    <p>
      Actual cost can change because appliances cycle on and off, use different settings, or draw less power
      after heating or cooling reaches a target. The calculator is best used as a planning estimate.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>Daily, monthly, and yearly cost</h2>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Period</th>
            <th>How to estimate</th>
            <th>Example from $1.02/day</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Daily</td>
            <td>Watts / 1000 x hours x rate</td>
            <td>$1.02</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Monthly</td>
            <td>Daily cost x 30</td>
            <td>$30.60</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Yearly</td>
            <td>Daily cost x 365</td>
            <td>$372.30</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section article-block">
    <h2>Common mistakes to avoid</h2>
    <p>
      The most common mistake is mixing up watts and kilowatt-hours. Watts describe the appliance's power
      draw. kWh describes energy used over time. Another common mistake is using 24 hours for a device that
      cycles. That can overestimate the cost of refrigerators, freezers, heat pumps, and some water heaters.
    </p>
    <p>
      It is also easy to overlook utility rate details. Some bills split electricity into supply, delivery,
      taxes, and fees. For everyday planning, an effective average rate from your bill is often more useful
      than only the supply rate.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section faq-list">
    <h2>Electricity cost FAQ</h2>
    <details open>
      <summary>What is the easiest way to estimate appliance cost?</summary>
      <p>
        Use the appliance wattage, hours used, and your electricity rate. Divide watts by 1,000 to get
        kilowatts, multiply by hours, then multiply by cost per kWh.
      </p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why does my actual bill not match the calculator exactly?</summary>
      <p>
        The calculator estimates appliance energy cost only. A bill can include other appliances, taxes,
        delivery charges, demand charges, seasonal rate changes, or time-of-use pricing.
      </p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Can I calculate cost from amps instead of watts?</summary>
      <p>
        Yes. Estimate watts by multiplying amps by volts, then use the same formula. For example, 10 amps at
        120 volts is about 1,200 watts.
      </p>
    </details>
  </section>

  <RelatedLinks
    title="Use the formula in a calculator"
    description="These calculators show how wattage, hours, and rate change the final cost."
    links={relatedCalculatorLinks}
  />

  <RelatedLinks
    title="Related electricity guides"
    description="Learn the pieces behind the formula before comparing more appliances."
    links={relatedGuideLinks}
  />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(articleSchema)} />
</BaseLayout>
